   "source": [
    "## 1. Introduction and Data Source\n",
    "\n",
    "The dataset selected for this project is **“CNC turning: roughness, forces and tool wear”**, obtained from Kaggle. This dataset was developed from controlled machining experiments conducted at the Competence Center in Manufacturing (CCM) at the Aeronautics Institute of Technology (ITA). The purpose of the experiments was to study how machining parameters influence key performance measures such as surface roughness, cutting forces, and tool wear.\n",
    "\n",
    "Because the data were collected under controlled laboratory conditions where factors were deliberately set by the experimenters, this dataset represents an **experimental study** rather than an observational one. This makes it especially appropriate for analysis using ANOVA techniques, as causal relationships between factors and the response variable can be investigated.\n",
    "\n",
    "---\n",
    "\n",
    "## 2. Description of Variables\n",
    "\n",
    "### Response Variable\n",
    "\n",
    "- **Surface Roughness (Ra):** A continuous numerical variable measuring the average deviation of the machined surface (in micrometers). Lower values indicate smoother surfaces.\n",
    "\n",
    "---\n",
    "\n",
    "### Factors (Independent Variables)\n",
    "\n",
    "- **Depth of Cut (ap):** 0.25, 0.5, 0.8 mm  \n",
    "- **Cutting Speed (vc):** 310, 350, 390 m/min  \n",
    "- **Feed Rate (f):** 0.07, 0.10, 0.13 mm/rev  \n",
    "\n",
    "---\n",
    "\n",
    "### Additional Variables\n",
    "\n",
    "- **Replica:** Indicates repeated experimental runs for the same factor combination  \n",
    "- **Position:** Measurement location on the machined surface  \n",
    "- **Run:** Constructed variable representing each unique experimental run  \n",
    "\n",
    "---\n",
    "\n",
    "## 3. Data Structure and Number of Observations\n",
    "\n",
    "The experimental design is a full factorial design:\n",
    "\n",
    "$$\n",
    "3 \\times 3 \\times 3 = 27 \\text{ treatment combinations}\n",
    "$$\n",
    "\n",
    "Each combination has:\n",
    "- 2 replicates  \n",
    "- 6 measurements per replicate  \n",
    "\n",
    "Total number of observations:\n",
    "\n",
    "$$\n",
    "27 \\times 2 \\times 6 = 324\n",
    "$$\n",
    "\n",
    "The design is **balanced at the treatment level**, meaning each factor combination has the same number of observations.\n",
    "\n",
    "---\n",
    "\n",
    "## 4. Potential Issues in the Data\n",
    "\n",
    "- **Non-independence**: Multiple measurements taken within the same replicate (run) are likely correlated, since they are collected under identical machining conditions. Treating these observations as independent would violate model assumptions.\n",
    "- **Hierarchical structure**: The data exhibit a nested structure, where measurements are nested within replicates, and replicates are nested within treatment combinations (ap × vc × f). This induces dependence that must be accounted for in the modeling process.\n",
    "- **Heteroscedasticity**: Preliminary diagnostics indicate that the variability of surface roughness is not constant across factor levels, particularly with respect to feed rate. This violates the assumption of constant variance required by standard ANOVA models.\n",
    "\n",
    "Ignoring these features would lead to underestimated variability, biased standard errors, and invalid statistical inferences .\n",
    "\n",
    "---\n",
    "\n",
    "## 5. Sample of the Data\n",
    "\n",
    "| ap   | vc  | f    | Ra   | Replica | Position |\n",
    "|------|-----|------|------|---------|----------|\n",
    "| 0.25 | 310 | 0.07 | 0.85 | 1       | 1        |\n",
    "| 0.25 | 310 | 0.07 | 0.88 | 1       | 2        |\n",
    "| 0.25 | 310 | 0.07 | 0.90 | 1       | 3        |\n",
    "| 0.25 | 310 | 0.07 | 0.87 | 1       | 4        |\n",
    "| 0.25 | 310 | 0.07 | 0.89 | 1       | 5        |\n",
    "| 0.25 | 310 | 0.07 | 0.86 | 1       | 6        |\n",
    "\n",
    "(This is a subset of one treatment combination; full dataset contains 324 observations.)\n",
    "\n",
    "---\n",
    "\n",
    "## 6. Proposed Analysis\n",
    "\n",
    "The analysis will use a **mixed-effects factorial ANOVA model**.\n",
    "\n",
    "- Fixed effects: ap, vc, f  \n",
    "- Random effect: Run (to account for repeated measurements)\n",
    "\n",
    "### Model:\n",
    "\n",
    "$$\n",
    "y_{ijkl} = \\mu + A_i + B_j + C_k + (AB)_{ij} + (AC)_{ik} + (BC)_{jk} + (ABC)_{ijk} + R_{l(ijk)} + \\epsilon_{ijkl}\n",
    "$$\n",
    "\n",
    "This model allows for:\n",
    "- Testing main effects  \n",
    "- Evaluating interaction effects  \n",
    "- Accounting for within-run variability  \n",
    "\n",
    "---\n",
    "\n",
    "## 7. Research Questions and Hypotheses\n",
    "\n",
    "1. Does depth of cut affect surface roughness?  \n",
    "2. Does cutting speed affect surface roughness?  \n",
    "3. Does feed rate affect surface roughness?  \n",
    "4. Are there interaction effects between factors?  \n",
    "5. Which factor has the strongest influence?  \n",
    "\n",
    "Each question corresponds to a hypothesis test where:\n",
    "\n",
    "- $H_0$: No effect  \n",
    "- $H_a$: Significant effect  \n",
    "\n",
    "---\n",
    "\n",
    "## 8. Summary\n",
    "\n",
    "This dataset provides a well-structured experimental framework for analyzing machining processes. Its factorial design combined with repeated measurements makes it ideal for mixed-effects ANOVA. The results will provide insight into how machining parameters influence surface roughness and demonstrate proper statistical modeling of hierarchical data."
   ]
