   "source": [
    "### 12.3 Key Results\n",
    "\n",
    "The results from regression coefficients and partial eta-squared values describe how machining parameters influence **variability in surface roughness (Ra)**. Feed rate is the dominant source of variance, followed by depth of cut and cutting speed. The direction of influence refers to how each factor changes the level of Ra and its variability.\n",
    "\n",
    "- **Feed rate (f):**\n",
    "  - Strongest contributor to variance in Ra\n",
    "  - Largest effect size (η² = 0.778)\n",
    "  - Strong **positive effect on variance level** (β = 7.234***): increasing feed rate increases surface roughness and overall variability\n",
    "  - Dominant factor controlling instability in surface finish\n",
    "\n",
    "- **Depth of cut (ap):**\n",
    "  - Moderate contribution to variance (η² = 0.331)\n",
    "  - Direction depends on level:\n",
    "    - ap = 0.5 → **reduces variance in Ra** (β = -0.294**)\n",
    "    - ap = 0.8 → slight **increase in variance** (β = 0.127, not significant)\n",
    "  - Indicates non-linear influence on process variability\n",
    "\n",
    "- **Cutting speed (vc):**\n",
    "  - Smaller contribution to variance (η² = 0.121)\n",
    "  - Directional effect varies:\n",
    "    - vc = 350 → negligible or slight **reduction in variance** (β = -0.031)\n",
    "    - vc = 390 → clear **increase in variance** (β = 0.377***)\n",
    "  - Higher cutting speeds tend to increase instability in surface roughness\n",
    "\n",
    "- **Interactions:**\n",
    "  - ap × vc shows meaningful contribution to variance (η² = 0.238), indicating combined effects on process stability\n",
    "  - ap × f and vc × f show moderate to weak contributions (η² ≈ 0.159 and 0.052)\n",
    "  - Three-way interaction contributes modestly (η² ≈ 0.159)\n",
    "\n",
    "- **Overall interpretation:**\n",
    "  - Single-factor models explain only a small portion of variance (~5–6%, R² ≈ 0.053–0.058)\n",
    "  - Combined model improves explanation of variance (R² = 0.164, RMSE = 0.70)\n",
    "  - Feed rate is the primary driver of increased variability in surface roughness, while other factors have secondary and interaction-dependent effects"
   ]
  },
